The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | Briefs
                                                                                                                     4                                                                                      BRIEFS
                  
	Calcutta, July 8: The state government today indicated there would not be any tripartite talks on the Gorkha Janmukti Morchas separate state demand unless normality was restored in the hills.    
	They (the Morcha) are calling prolonged bandhs and then demanding tripartite talks. This cant be accepted, home secretary Samar Ghosh said.    
	The Morcha had threatened a 40-day strike in the hills from next month if the date for the talks was not announced immediately.         
	Santiniketan: The students unions at Visva-Bharati, led by the Trinamul Congress and the Congress, on Thursday called an indefinite strike to protest a fee hike that came into effect from this month. The tuition fee for undergraduate students has been raised from Rs 18 a month to Rs 100 and that for postgraduate students from Rs 20 to Rs 120.        
	Jhargram: Manik Mahato, one of the alleged plotters of the Jnaneswari Express sabotage, was on Thursday remanded in 10 days police custody. Maoist leader Manik, who the police claimed was a bigger catch than prime accused Bapi Mahato, was arrested on Wednesday from Orissa.                                                                                                                                                      
